<h1 id="apron">Apron</h1>

<p><img src="/assets/Apron/ApronBlank.jpg" onmouseover="this.src='/assets/Apron/ApronFull.jpg';" onmouseout="this.src='/assets/Apron/ApronBlank.jpg';" /></p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Permanent-Marker-Regular-Chisel-AVE07887/dp/B001JQBIW8/ref=sr_1_5?s=office-products&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1495982840&amp;sr=1-5">Red Chisel Point Permanent Marker</a> - I use this for marking waste and metal bits.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Pentel-Automatic-Drafting-Brushed-PG1015A/dp/B000GAU2RU/ref=sr_1_1?s=office-products&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1495982916&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=pentel+graphgear+1000">Pentel GraphGear 1000 0.5mm</a> - My main <em>writing</em> pencil</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="http://www.zebrapen.com/product/m-301-mechanical-pencil/">Zebra 0.5mm mechanical pencil (First generation)</a> - Backup <em>writing</em> pencil. I don’t always want to mess around with lead</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/uni-ball-KuruToga-Mechanical-Pencil-0-7mm/dp/B00BEYXGPC/ref=sr_1_3?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1495983365&amp;sr=8-3&amp;keywords=uni-ball+diamond">Uni-Ball KuroToga 0.5mm</a> - My <em>marking</em> pencil. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Strength-Uni-ball-0-5mm-HB-Original-Description/dp/B00U6UQK7Q/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1495983365&amp;sr=8-2&amp;keywords=uni-ball+diamond">Uni-Ball Diamond Infused Lead</a> is the real deal. You can mark on very rough wood without breaking your lead.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0006O87TQ/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&amp;psc=1">Olfa Ak-1 Hobby knife</a> - I use this for various cutting activities. See my review on that link under “Robert Randolph”.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="http://www.leevalley.com/us/Wood/page.aspx?p=67466">Veritas Dual Marking Guage</a> - Second/Third use, tenon and rabbet marking guage.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="http://www.leevalley.com/us/wood/page.aspx?p=59455">Veritas Non-graduated Micro-adjust marking guage</a> - First-use marking guage</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000ETWQ4U/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&amp;psc=1">Empire Level Combination Square</a> - Knock-around combo square I use for most things. Reliable, square and an excellent product for the price.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="http://www.leevalley.com/us/wood/page.aspx?p=69309&amp;cat=1,43415,43440&amp;ap=1">McQueen’s Mutton Tallow</a> - Lubricant and anti-rust agent that I’m constantly using on my tools. Way better than oil! More slippery and lasts longer per application.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="https://www.japanwoodworker.com/products/5-8-blue-steel-marking-knife">Aogami Ambidextrous Marking Knife</a> - Primary marking knife.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="https://www.harborfreight.com/hand-tools/hammers/5-piece-fiberglass-handle-ball-pein-hammer-set-39217.html">13 oz Harbor Freight Ball Peen Hammer</a> - I love this hammer set. I use the peening end for burnishing dowel ends, and it’s been a workhorse since I started building my shop.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>Also note that the center pocket is not fully sewn. It has 3 tacks at the bottom so that dust and chips can easily fall through, but larger items stay in place.</p>

<h1 id="knife-holder">Knife Holder</h1>

<p><img src="/assets/Apron/KnifeOut.jpg" onmouseover="this.src='/assets/Apron/KnifeIn.jpg';" onmouseout="this.src='/assets/Apron/KnifeOut.jpg';" /></p>

<p>I made a walnut sheath for the <a href="https://www.japanwoodworker.com/products/5-8-blue-steel-marking-knife">Aogami Ambidextrous Marking Knife</a>. The Apron has a flap over one of the vertical belt-level tool holders, and the top of the flat is sewn so only the knife can be pulled out, and not the sheath.</p>

<p>The sheath barely slips in through the flap and vertical holder. The sheath has a wide channeled opening to guide the knife in without causing any damage to the nearby fabric.</p>

<p>It’s an elegant, functional and simple way to have a knife always at hand without any risk.</p>

